{:id "war-machine/ambient-pattern-retrieval"
 :claim "A library of reusable strategies that is searched automatically on every conversation turn functions as ambient intelligence — the system's background awareness of what it knows, surfaced without being asked."
 :ground "futon3a's pattern library (853 patterns) is searched via MiniLM embeddings on every A→B turn in the REPL. Results appear as desktop notifications with evidence certificates. The operator does not request the search — it happens as a side-effect of working. Over time, the activation pattern across the library reveals which strategies are repeatedly relevant (hot zones) and which are never activated (cold zones)."
 :warrant "Expert practitioners develop intuitions that surface relevant knowledge without deliberate recall. A chess grandmaster sees threats without counting squares. Ambient retrieval externalises this: the system maintains a background awareness of its own knowledge and surfaces relevant pieces as the situation evolves. The activation history across the library is the system's version of an expert's trained intuition."
 :backing "Per-turn context retrieval is operational (MiniLM embeddings installed, notifications firing). Evidence certificates log which patterns activated for which turn. The activation frequency distribution reveals library hot zones and cold zones — a kind of MRI of the system's active knowledge."
 :qualifier "Ambient retrieval quality depends on embedding quality and library coverage. Current MiniLM embeddings are generic, not domain-fine-tuned. Retrieval is post-hoc (what just happened) not pre-hoc (what's about to be needed). Pre-hoc requires enough post-hoc data to train a predictor."
 :rebuttal "Notification fatigue: if every turn triggers a notification with low-relevance patterns, the operator will learn to ignore them. The retrieval must earn attention by being relevant, or it becomes noise."
 :tension "A large knowledge base exists but is only useful when the right pieces surface at the right time."
 :resolution "Search the library on every turn as a background process. Display results as ambient notifications, not interruptions. Log the activation history as evidence. Use the activation pattern to diagnose library hot/cold zones and to train pre-hoc prediction."}
